            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> there doesn't seem to be a good way to wait until all output is available in the window.\n\nHow can Nvim know when \"all output\" is done? More output may arrive at any time.\n\nIIUC it sounds like you want a way to identify when the payload sent by `nvim_chan_send` was fully processed. One way to do that would be some sort of `on_foo` handler:\n\n```lua\nlocal s = \"hello\\r\\nworld\\r\\n\"\nlocal term_id = vim.api.nvim_open_term(bufnr, {\n  on_foo(raw, rendered) {\n    if raw == s then\n      vim.print('all output was rendered')\n    end\n  }\n})\nvim.api.nvim_chan_send(term_id, s)\n```\n\nbut that's clumsy, because `on_foo` may invoke on \"partial\" results...\n\nAlternative approach (which I've also proposed for `nvim_input`), is to identify the `nvim_chan_send(term_id, s)` input with a unique \"ticket\", which can be used later to find it in the \"stream\":\n\n```lua\nlocal orig = \"hello\\r\\nworld\\r\\n\"\nlocal ticket_id --@type number?\nlocal term_id = vim.api.nvim_open_term(bufnr, {\n  on_foo(ticket, ...) {\n    if ticket == ticket_id then\n      vim.print('all output was rendered')\n    end\n  }\n})\nticket_id = vim.api.nvim_chan_send(term_id, orig)\n```\n\nor maybe simpler, just pass a `on_foo(byte_offset)` that tracks the length of the entire data that the terminal has processed. However, that again would be awkward if multiple producers are writing to the same channel.\n\nCan someone show an actual proposal of what they expect here?",
